<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Mencap response to</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mencap</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Mencap</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">We support the 1.5 million people with a learning disability in the </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> and their families and carers. We fight to change laws and improve services and access to education, employment and leisure facilities, supporting thousands of people with a learning disability to live their lives the way they want. See </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">www.mencap.org.uk </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">for more information. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">We are also one of the largest providers of services, information and advice for people with a learning disability across England, Northern Ireland and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About learning disability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">A learning disability is caused by the way t</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">he brain develops before, during or shortly after birth. It is always lifelong and affects someone's intellectual and social development. It used to be called mental handicap but this term is outdated and offensive. Learning disability is </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">not</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> a mental illn</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ess. The term learning difficulty is often incorrectly used interchangeably with learning disability.</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap’s vision is for a truly inclusive society, where people with a learning disability </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">are valued equally, and get the support they need to live fulfilling lives.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">We welcome the International Development Committee’s inquiry into Disability and Development, with a focus on ensuring disabled people are included in international development p</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">rogrammes.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">This submission focuses on the important principles which underpin inclusive education and inclusive employment practice.</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> Many of these principles will underpin inclusive practice in relation to other areas of people’s lives as well. We hope a sha</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">red understanding of these prin</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ples will </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">help </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ensure that people with a learning disability are fully included in development pr</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ogrammes.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Inclusive education practice</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap believe that children and young people with a learning disability should be educated within their local communities alongside their brothers, sisters, friends and neighbours where they are enabled to reach their full potential. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Children with a lear</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ning disability should attend a school in their local community that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Achieves good educational outcomes;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Provides teachers who are trained to support the needs of all children;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Supports access to excellent specialist support;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Has a flexible approach to th</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">e development of curricula that are relevant to every child’s learning potential;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Has an ethos that values diversity and recognises the mutual contribution of children and young people with and without a learning disability being educated together.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">We supp</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ort the policy of progressive realisation set out in the UN Convention. This recognises the importance of moving towards a system of mainstream educational provision which can provide for all disabled children, and which enables them to succeed in all area</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">s of school life. Mencap recognises that for some children, because of the nature of their support needs, there will always be the need for specialist support, but believes that this can be developed in a range of settings that facilitate inclusion and eng</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">agement within the local community. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">These include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Specialist support units within a “mainstream” setting;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Special schools or units co-located within a “mainstream” setting;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Specialist support delivered into “mainstream” schools from a separate setting;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">pecialist schools and units located near or next to mainstream setting with some sharing of facilities;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Pupils who are jointly enrolled in a specialist and mainstream setting.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap’s aspirations for the inclusion of children with a learning disability </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">within mainstream school settings is based on the belief that there must be robust alternatives to the way that special educational needs are currently provided for in segregated settings before parents could feel confident for their children to be educate</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">d in inclusive settings as above.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap believes that for children with learning disabilities to be able to grow up in a world that includes them in all areas of society, they must have equal opportunities to engage with their peers from all backgrounds,</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> be equipped with personal skills to progress and have presence as a valued member in the community.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Practice guidance around inclusive education</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Currently, the SEN Code of Practice sets out the practice guidance for professionals working with children and</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> young people with Special </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Educational Needs (SEN)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> In addition to this, the government has also issued Inclusive Schooling guidance that sets out practical advice for schools and local authorities on inclusive practices.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> The guidance promotes 7 key prin</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ciples of an inclusive education service:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Inclusion is a process by which schools, local education authorities and others develop their cultures, policies and practices to include pupils;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">With the right training, strategies and support nearly all children </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">with SEN can be successfully included in mainstream education;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">An inclusive education service offers excellence and choice and incorporates the views of parents and children;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The interes</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ts o</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">f all pupils must be safeguarded;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">School, local education authorit</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ies and others should actively seek to remove barriers to learning and participation;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">All children should have access to an appropriate education that affords them the opportunity to achieve their person</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> potential;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mainstream education</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> will not always be</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> right for every child all of the child. Equally just because mainstream education may not be right at a particular stage it does not prevent the child from being included successfully at a later stage.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">It goes further to state that inclusive schools have:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">An inclusive ethos;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">A broad and balanced curriculum for all pupils;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Systems for early identification of barriers to learning and participation; and</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">High expectations and suitable targets for all children.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The SEN system is currently being reformed as part</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> of the Children and Families Bill that is passing through Parliament. As part of these reforms, (due to be implemented as of September 2014) the current Code of Practice and the Inclusive Schooling guidance is being merged into a single 0-25 SEN Code of P</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ractice.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The draft version of this document is still not finalised, but it has several sections on inclusion, principally set out on pages 86-88. For example it sets out that "where a child or young person has SEN but does not have an EHC plan they must b</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">e educated in a mainstream setting barring very certain circumstances".</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The new Code of Practice also refers to the provisions of the Equality Act, which include school and local authority duties not to discriminate against, and must make reasonable adjust</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ments for, disabled children. Public bodies are also under wider duties to promote equality of opportunity.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Inclusive employment practice</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">People with a learning disability are more excluded from the workplace than any other group of disabled people. Research shows 65% of people with a learning disability want to work, and that with the right support they make highly valued employees. However</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">, only 7% of adults with a learning disability are in paid employment, and even then it is often for part-time hours and low pay. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap believes that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">people with a learning disability should have access to good-quality further education and training;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">pe</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ople with a learning disability should be properly supported to get into work, and in the workplace;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">more employers should take on people with a learning disability;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">employers must pay people with a learning disability at least the national minimum wage fo</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">r the work they do;</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">There are many barriers to people with a learning disability accessing employment, including employer prejudice. However, Mencap believes that people with a learning disability should also get the support they need to get and keep real </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">paid jobs in mainstream settings and that, in order to help achieve this, the government should increase supported employment provision for people with a learning disability and guarantee long-term funding for this support. The definition of supported empl</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">oyment is as follows:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">A way of enabling people who need additional assistance to succeed in work;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Real, paid jobs in a non-segregated environment. i.e. not sheltered workshops where only other disabled people work. And not makeshift work designed simply to</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> keep the person occupied;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Full employee entitlements with wages at the going rate for the job;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The right job for the right person, found through vocational profiling and job analysis;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">A job that meets the employer’s needs because the disabled person is a </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">good employee performing tasks that the employer needs to be performed. There should never be any tokenism;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">A support organisation provides help in the areas where the employer or employee needs support. This will often involve job-coaching. There is a lon</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">g-term commitment to provide support for just as long as is necessary.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">This model is based on a number of important principles:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">The social model of disability: the difficulties that individuals face can be dealt with in terms of support, and by addressing </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">systematic barriers to inclusion;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">All disabled people may wish to access work, and no individual or group should be assumed to be unemployable. This does not mean that people who do not wish to work should be coerced into doing so;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Potential workers do not</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt"> need to be ‘work ready’ before they can access supported employment. The best place to undergo training and learn about work is at work;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Success is not defined in terms of people who no longer need support or no longer use benefits. There are people who w</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ill need assistance to maintain their job on a more or less permanent basis. Success does not necessarily mean a complete lack of support.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">In order to foster a truly inclusive society, Mencap believes that people with a learning disability should be proper</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ly and meaningfully included in the workplace and be given the opportunity to get and hold down a job. Employers should make reasonable adjustments where required and, in addition to these obligations, Access to Work funding is available to pay for aids an</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">d adaptations, transport costs, a communicator at a job interview, a support worker job coaches. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Practice guidance around inclusive</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">Mencap has produced its 'I Want To Work' guide for employers that highlights good p</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">ractice in employing people with a </span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">learning disability</span><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Mencap'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130401151715/https://www.education.gov.uk/publications/eOrderingDownload/0581-2001-SEN-CodeofPractice.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130401151715/https://www.education.gov.uk/publications/eOrde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ringDownload/DfES-0774-2001.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">https://www.education.gov.uk/consultations/downloadableDocs/Draft%20SEN%20Code%20of%20Practice.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.mencap.org.uk/sites/default/files/documents/2008-10/LDW_factsheets_ENG.pdf.</span></p></body></html>